  "timeframe": "30m",
  "market_context": "Bullish directional bias established on higher timeframe; price had swept sell-side liquidity below prior lows, entered accumulation near an order block and fair value gap; London session opening provided confirmation candle with new FVG for entry.",
  "key_observation": "Price wicked below a key low (liquidity sweep), closed back above it, then formed a bullish displacement with a clear FVG—signaling smart money accumulation and high-probability long entry zone.",
  "analysis_steps": [
    "Step 1: Identify overall directional bias as bullish based on higher-timeframe structure and market context.",
    "Step 2: Locate key liquidity levels—specifically sell-side liquidity (SSL) below recent swing lows—and wait for price to sweep it.",
    "Step 3: Observe price wick below the low and close back above, confirming manipulation and reversal potential.",
    "Step 4: Identify the resulting accumulation phase with an order block (OB) and fair value gap (FVG) in the 30-minute chart as the entry zone.",
    "Step 5: Enter long within the FVG (also identified as inverted FVG), placing stop loss at the invalidated low (invalidation point).",
    "Step 6: Target upper liquidity pool (buy-side liquidity) near prior swing highs; take partial profits at 1:3 risk-reward when price approached that zone and NY session opened.",
    "Step 7: Move stop to break-even after logical high shift; exit remaining position at break-even ahead of FOMC event due to increased uncertainty."
  ],
  "outcome": "Half position taken off at 1:3 risk-reward (~1.11400), remaining half exited at break-even before FOMC; no loss, partial profit realized.",
  "lessons": "Trade only after liquidity is swept and structure confirms bias; use FVG/OB for precise entries; always align stop placement with invalidation points; manage partials logically—not emotionally—especially before macro events.",
